value.value: A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the short arm of chromosome 10 (10p).
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the long arm of chromosome 16 (16q).
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the long arm of chromosome 10 (10q).
A chromosomal abnormality consisting of the translocation of genetic material from any one of several chromosomes to the 11q23.3 region, resulting in an MLL gene rearrangement.
Localized swelling of the eyelid due to blockage of the meibomian glands, usually caused by inflammation.

A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to a chromosomal translocation involving the long arm (q22) of chromosome 17 and the long arm (q13) of chromosome 22. It is associated with the expression of COL1A1/PDGFB fusions and most if not all cases of dermatofibrosarcoma protuberans (DFSP).

A cytogenetic aneuploidy abnormality that refers to the presence of one chromosome 5 only. It is associated with the development of refractory anemia with excess blasts, refractory anemia with multilineage dysplasia, and refractory anemia with multilineage dysplasia and ringed sideroblasts.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to loss of all or part of chromosome 7.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to loss of all or part of chromosome 5.

A chromosomal abnormality characterized by the presence of three copies of genetic material for chromosome 13, instead of the normal two. It leads to a variety of abnormalities that include mental retardation, microcephaly, low-set ears, eye structural defects, polydactyly, and limb abnormalities.
A granuloma located on the orbit of the eye.
A chromosomal abnormality consisting of the presence of a third copy of chromosome 4 in somatic cells.

A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the translocation of the short arm (p22.3) of chromosome 6 and the long arm (q34.1) of chromosome 9. It is associated with DEK/NUP214 fusions, acute myeloid leukemia and myelodysplastic syndromes.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the deletion of the chromosomal band 11q23.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to loss of all or part of chromosome 8.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to loss of all or part of chromosome 13.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to loss of all or part of the X chromosome.

A non-neoplastic lesion characterized by the proliferation of keratinizing squamous epithelium in the middle ear that results in the accumulation of keratin and cells.  It is usually caused by repeated infections.  If left untreated, it may increase in size and destroy the adjacent delicate bones of the middle ear.
Any change in the structure of one or more chromosomes.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to loss of all or part of chromosome 16.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the long arm of chromosome 17 (17q).
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the short arm of chromosome 2 (2p).
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the long arm of chromosome 2 (2q).
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to loss of all or part of chromosome 11.
As accumulation of granulation tissue in the middle ear that results from the degeneration of blood and a chronic inflammatory response.
